The artist is very good at manipulating similar melodies from different themes. This arrangement is composed of two themes, and I couldn't tell which part is which theme upon first listening. th08_06.comment:
I made the pdf based on BZ's video.
Note that the B part (measure 9-24) and the C part (measure 25-32) both have a 3-voice texture, with middle voice split between two hands. The left hand part of the middle voice is not explicitly written in some measures (for example 12-13) so don't forget to emphasize them.
The D part (starting at measure 33) has a furious left hand pattern, which is the main difficulty of this arrangement. It may seem unnecessary but I feel the regular eighth note accompaniment sounds empty after listening to this version.
The A' part (last page) has some additional notes compared to the A part, but the difference can hardly be heard. I prefer 柊秀雪's method: move the notes higher (actually the same as the original midi) and assign them to the left hand (with hand crossing). See https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EkxE3hb4UE0

th10_11_3.comment:
Some corrections to the score: 
The leading tone B# is denoted as C♮ throughout the score. It doesn't affect the sound, but is slightly difficult to sight-read. 
In measure 44, the first chord should have a top note of E. In measure 50, the third note should be a trill on B. 
In measure 52, the first chord should have a top note of E which is a trill. 
 In measure 113, the ornament should be G#-B. 
In measure 115, the ornament should be A-C#. In measure 121, the ornament should be B-D#. 
In measure 139, the second half of right hand should be 3-3-1-1 rhythm instead of 2-2-2-2 (unit = 16th note). 
In measure 149, the triplets should be four 16th notes, the last one being a B. 
Measure 157 chord omits the top note E#.

th11_14.comment:
This is not an ideal version for me but I put it here anyways for discussion. I may as well make an arrangement myself but it's not easy to play and I'm too lazy to practice (lol). 

1. The beginning omits a part of melody but exposes the bass line and brings freshness, so I think it's an acceptable modification. By the way, the bass line has a hidden melody which goes (Bb - Ab - G - Ab) x2 then (G - F - Eb - F) x2. Some other versions (for example marasy's) make it explicit. 
2. Measures 5-8 provides an easy way to play the fast part (and probably the most difficult part in the whole piece). The left hand tremolo (or any 16th-note sequence) is critical here, or else it wouldn't sound fast. If the tremolo is still difficult perhaps hold the lowest key (F or Db) for each harmonic change, reducing it to single-note tremolo. 
3. Measure 9 onwards: I don't know why there is an extra 16th note in each 3/8 beat. Four 16th notes + one 8th note is much easier to play than six 16th notes without breaks, not to mention the extra note should be played lighter to contrast the melody, which is more work. Some details in the original theme: the second 3/8 beat is F - Eb - F - C - Ab - C as opposed to F - Eb - F - Ab - G - Ab on the score; the last 3/8 beat has 1 - 1 - 2 - 1 - 1 rhythm, which is correct in this arrangement (marasy's version is 1 - 1 - 1 - 1 - 2). 
4. The first measure on page 4 has rhythm 3 - 3 - 2 but the original rhythm is 3 - 1 - 4. Disregarding the rhythm, I like the voicing setup here – F and G being the two most noticeable notes and the other three notes hidden under an octave. In fact, the last three notes in every phrase coincide with the bass melody, so you may as well not play them at all and let the left hand ring from a distance. 
5. The first two measures on page 6 sound like this in the original theme: F - G - C - F - Ab - F - C - G | F - Ab - C - F - A - F - C - F. The raised middle note (A natural) in the second measure is obvious while I'm not sure about other notes. 
 6. The bass used in page 6 sounds very off, especially when right hand is at a long rest. The original theme uses a bass that has its strong beats on 3 and 6 (counting 8 beats per measure) and marasy's version fits it perfectly (measure 46 for your reference).
